<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>rural transport for the UK government for PTUC</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Written evidence from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Public Transport Users</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> Committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> for Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt"> (TIC 110)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ntroduction</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Public Transport Users’ Committee for Wales (PTUC) welcomes the opportunity to contribute to this inquiry.  </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The PTUC is a committee which offers advice to Welsh Ministers about strategic issues relating to public transport services in Wales from the perspective of users’ experiences and needs.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The present arrangements relating to Wales are that although much of the control over rural transport has been devolved to Wales there remains a degree of overall regulation and statutory frameworks that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the remit of Westminster. We felt it was thus </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">appropriate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for PTUC (Wales) to make a submission on this issue.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In terms of rural transport, especially in terms of the bus and community transport sectors, the detailed specifications and funding streams are within the remit of Welsh Government, and it is mainly at this level that service frequencies, connections and much in the way of quality of provision is specified. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Rural transport is of critical importance because of its impact on health and well-being, and the positive impact improved connectivity can play in promoting economic renewal and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">helping reduce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> poverty. Rural public transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">promotes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">social inclusion, while having a role to play in reducing the environmental cost of transport.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> It is our view that at present users are not at the heart of service delivery and this can lead to services that are optimised around provider needs rather than around the needs of the user.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wales is a predominantly rural nation, and a major concern is that the provision of rural public transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">relies heavily on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> community transport, which is patchy and generally not developed strategically.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The regulation of bus services in rural areas and anti-competitive laws act in a way to reduce co-ordination of low frequency services. Regulations which may well have a place in an urban setting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> where competition occurs between commercial service providers, is wholly unsuited to rural and deeply rural regions with a mix of low frequency commercial and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">supported </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">services. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How do Government and local authorities identify demand for passenger transport in isolated communities (including rural and urban areas and island communities)?</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The focus is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on existing users who may have a voice for example </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">through</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bus Users UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their bus surgeries. Non-users tend not to be considered, and public transport planning, especially in rural areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is likely to be reactive rather than proactive when new developments occur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ublic transport is usually considered after the location of a new development has been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">finalised,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rather than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">seeking the optimum location on the basis of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> public transport access.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent are the needs of different groups of passengers (e.g. people with disabilities, older people, young people) taken into account in determining the provision of public transport to isolated communities?</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rural Wales</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> there are some bus services that run once per week on a market day in the nearest town. These are designed around access for shopping and medical appointments. Outside of school and college transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> little consideration </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is given to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the needs of young people. Similarly, little consideration is given to running late evening buses to allow visits to cinemas, concerts etc. There are instances where service timetables are based around operator convenience rather than users, so there may not be a late bus on a Friday or Saturday or to meet an evening train </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">due to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a lack of flexibility in drivers hours etc. There remains a concern that some vehicles remain inaccessible for disabled passengers. Or that space on vehicles is taken up by others, such </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as passengers with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> child buggies, which can lead to conflict.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What are the main challenges associated with providing better and more consistent bus and rail services to isolated communities? How can these challenges be overcome?</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Integration between modes and between different operators is critical. Rural public transport timetables will generally be low frequency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> possibly two hourly or worse. The robustness of connections is then far more important than journey time. Regulation and anti-competitive requirements prevent many operators from co-ordinating services so that an appropriate service can be provided at an economic cost.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Uncertainties about longer-term revenue support also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">raise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> issue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. People will make employment, educational or home location decisions based upon public transport timetables and routes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> change to these could seriously affect the continued viability of such decisions. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How effectively do Community Transport services address the needs of passengers in isolated communities? How could Community Transport be improved?</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Community transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is usually locally based and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">can be very patchy, with some excellent examples. Publicity tends to be focused on local, regular users. A big issue in the sector remains how to get non-users to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">realise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">what is available, and that the service is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">available </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The variable and local nature of community transport makes it difficult for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">potential </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">users from outside the area to make use of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Spreading good practice to areas with less community transport needs to be considered</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Workshops, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">where practitioners and potential users could develop and understand what is available</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are a useful tool</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to release the potential in this sector.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent should passengers in isolated communities be expected to rely on taxis and other demand-responsive transport services?</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Development of demand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">led services such as bwc-a-bus in Carmarthenshire is one possible solution. Consideration needs to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">given </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to existing users of timetabled services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, if these are to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be replaced by a demand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-responsive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">system. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What are the main challenges associated with funding transport services in isolated communities? How can these services be made more affordable?</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Unit costs of traditional public transport are high, and policies that act against integration of public transport services have pushed many rural inhabitants towards the private car. This has reduced the viability and thus the service frequency of many bus routes, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and removed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">many rural railway stations from the network.  Increasing usage will make services more financially viable and this requires a concerted effort to target</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> current</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> non-users. For this group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> information on service timetables, access, how to purchase tickets, inter-availability of tickets and accurate, updated information </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in case</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of delay</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are critically important.  </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oncerns about road congestion, which are a major driver of increased public transport use in urban areas, are less of a driver in rural areas.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:15.6pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Observations</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At present</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with devolved Governments in Wales and Scotland having differing levels of responsibility over transport, there is an uncertainty over transport planning. For instance rail infrastructure in Wales remains the responsibility of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the UK Government, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">while </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there is some Welsh Government input into </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">service levels </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Arriva Wales franchise l. Bus services </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in Wales </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are funded via </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">four </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regional transport consortia in alliance with local Authorities for funded services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> while the market determines service timetables on commercial routes. The lack of an overarching view is thus a major issue when integration is considered. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wales has seen the development of a demand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">led rural bus service, called bwc-a-bus, which has replaced previously very infrequent timetabled services in some areas. The scheme has been designed to be more responsive to passengers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> needs. The introduction of bwc-a-bus has seen some inertia by users of the previous timetabled services, and the move from a sparse timetabled service to a bwc-a-bus type demand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">led service needs to win the hearts and minds of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">both existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">users (and potential ones. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A number of recent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have highlighted the issue of the rising </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">percentage of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">population </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">facing transport poverty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> meaning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that the rising cost of transport leaves people excluded and isolated, unable to access opportunities, from jobs to healthcare, that many take for granted. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consideration also needs to be given to younger people. As motoring costs rise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> many young people are now delaying driving tests for cost reasons, particularly the high cost of insurance for younger drivers. In rural areas this results in youngsters having to rely on sparse public transport, which seriously restricts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">access to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">employment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">opportunities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. A recurring theme is the lack of evening bus services in rural areas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reducing opportunities for evening activities such as visits to the cinema or friends</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, while also removing the chance of working in sectors involving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evening or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shift work. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consideration should be given to the wider impact of rural passenger transport. Community transport is a lifeline for many users. It enables some users to remain living in their own homes for longer, reducing costs for health and social services. Similarly, for people with disabilities, removal of rural public or community transport could well result in increased healthcare or social services costs.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8.6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As health services become ever more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">centralised </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in specialist units</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">accessibility to these services needs to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">carefully </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">considered. We already see in Wales that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">one hour public transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">journeys to the local general hospital</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be replaced by the need for very lengthy journeys involving multiple c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hanges and unfamiliar locations.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:15.6pt; margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 21.25pt; text-indent:-21.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>